    Note: this limiter is in-memory, good for local/single-process deployment. For serious production scale, the next upgrade should move rate-limit counters to Redis so limits work across multiple server instances.

        That’s totally okay. You do not need Redis right now.

        For where the project is today, the in-memory rate limiter I added is enough to protect the app during development and early launch. It costs nothing and requires no extra service.

        The tradeoff is simple:

        Works well when backend runs as one server/process.
        Resets when the server restarts.
        If Render/production runs multiple instances, each instance has its own limit counter.
        Not perfect against serious abuse, but much better than having no protection.
        For now I’d keep it this way.

        Later, when the app starts getting real traffic or money, Redis becomes useful for:

        shared rate limiting across servers
        Celery background jobs
        caching
        session/device state
        notification queues
        But today, we can avoid that cost. A good low-cost path is:

        Keep in-memory rate limiting now.
        Keep Celery/Redis code as “production-ready foundation,” but don’t enable BACKGROUND_JOBS_ENABLED=true yet.
        Continue sending emails directly as fallback.
        When money/traffic arrives, add Redis through Render, Upstash, Railway, or another provider.

